title: Adafruit Pi Box - With LCD & RS232 DB9

description.text: Modified Adafruit's Raspberry Pi Box to accomidate Longtech 16x2 LCD Module. Also added RS232 port on side. With a Max3232 chip you could turn the TTL UART pins into RS232 level.

LCD could be purchased here:
http://nkcelectronics.webstorepowered.com/16x2-Module-white-Backlight-Arduino/dp/B007LO3Y9W Code to drive the LCD via Python is provided by my friend, and fellow FamiLAB member, Lance "lrvick": https://github.com/lrvick/raspi-hd44780 I used four 2-56 threaded 1/2" screws to hold the LCD in with.
You Could purchase them as a part of a pack from Radioshack:
http://www.radioshack.com/product/index.jsp?productId=2103300 Three hex nuts for each screw was used makeshift standoffs. The same nuts screwed the LCD into place.
The nuts were also bought from Radioshack:
http://www.radioshack.com/product/index.jsp?productId=2103302 This is all sized for 3mm acrylic. With three nuts as standoff, LCD is flush. Blue Vectors are inside cuts
Green Vectors are for Outside cuts
Red should be treated as raster.
Black should be cut as Raster, do not cut them as vectors as you'll have too large holes. If you desire recessed screws: My hackerspace has a 40 watt Full Spectrum Hobbiest Laser Cutter. I cut at 15% speed, 100% power, 1000DPI in Retina Engrave with laser set to 10mA. This etched deep into the acrylic around screw holes for LCD to allow recessed screws. This is optional, and should only be used on the file with the black circles though. I put the LCD panel mount in a seperate SVG, so you won't have a conflict with the raster settings of the red text.

The coils on the ends of the generic spring are squished together but not ground flat like on the aftermarket medium Kronos spring, which has a 21mm OD and 3.37mm wire diameter.

description.text: Print your own US Flag keychain fob. This print is intended for printing with a printer which supports "pause @ Z position". This keychain was inspired by Jetty's Canadian flag keychain fob, Thing #26139, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26139 Update: and, it turns out, Jetty just published a US flag fob as well (but I scooped Jetty :) http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26141 P.S. Feel free to figure out the cut depths for the keys. They're not for my house or jet plane.

• Slice the us-flag STL with a 0.3 mm layer height.
  • Print he first layer using white or natural uncolored ABS.
  • As the first layer is printing, note the Z height of the print head. Call this height Z0
  • Enable the "pause @ zpos" function. Set the pause to be at Z0 + 6*0.3 = Z0 + 1.8.
  • When the printer pauses, switch to a blue colored filament.
  • Resume the printing.
  • Again, enable the "pause @ zpos" function. Set the pause to be at Z0 + 8*0.3 = Z0 + 2.4.
  • When the printer pauses, switch to a red colored filament.
    • In the above calculations, the 0.3 is the layer height which was used in the OpenSCAD model. If you want to use a different layer height, then edit the OpenSCAD model changing the value of the "l_h" parameter to the layer height which you wish to use. Then render the keychain and export a new STL file.

title: D-Bot X carriage for Piezo Z probe and Titan Aero
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is my first functional carriage for a D-bot corexy using a piezo for z-probing.

I am using the Precision Piezo circuit.

Still in development, seems to work ok now but will probably add a place to affix the circuit (at the moment it is tack glued)

Flip the hinged support to print, everything should work without need of support.

You can get STP or other format files if you want to alter stuff here.

For part cooling I am using this support with a blower fan (I cut the parts that conflict with the carriage).

The idea here is adding a 27mm piezo disk to the recess, and use m3x20 screws + nuts to do the 'hinge' part, and m3x12 to close the 'door' like. Don't get the screws too tight, you want it to have a little bit of flex.

The lever effect of the hinged support will translate the pressure on the Titan nozzle to the piezo. It's pretty efficient, really.

When you add the piezo disk, you should be able to press the hinged support and feel the disk flexing under it.

There's a different mount with a 20mm piezo slot instead of 27mm. Untested but should work, plz report.

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6oKbeM-Szjo
This Thing represents a model which is a basis for studying radiant or flyback energy. It is a compact design. The original designs and applications for these motors should be credited to John Bedini and Ron Cole. I reworked this motor to make it easy for those across seas to source the magnets and hardware. It also has some upgrades. A good place to learn about this technology is here: http://www.energyscienceforum.com/forumdisplay.php?f=48
The moderators worked closely with John Bedini and understand this technology well.

Parts:
6 magnets: 40mm X 10mm X 5mm https://www.magnetexpert.com/rectangular-magnets-c35/40-x-10-x-5mm-thick-n42-neodymium-magnet-8-3kg-pull-p3790 also http://www.magnets365.com/10pcs-40mm-x-10mm-x-5mm-block-cuboid-rare-earth-neodymium-magnets-n50-grade.html for a pack of 10
12 M4 pan head bolts at least 10mm long for the rotor caps 6 per side
8 M5 pan head bolts at least 50mm long 4 per side
8 M5 pan head bolts for mounting the motor 4 top and 4 bottom (optional)
2 8mm X 22mm X 7mm skateboard bearings. I highly recommend ABEC 5+ or Swiss Bearings: https://bonesbearings.com/bones-reg-swiss-skateboard-bearings-8-pack
The wire and the circuit is up to you.
1 8mm shaft rod
3 5mm X 5mm disc magnets for reed or hall triggering (optional) https://www.magnetexpert.com/circular-disc-rod-magnets-c34/5mm-dia-x-5mm-thick-n42-neodymium-magnet-0-9kg-pull-p3558
Print with infill set at 30%..tops and bottoms .8mm...walls 1.2mm....2mm layer height.
You are contending with strong centripetal forces.
Please review https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1676878 to have an idea how this should fit together. I use a table vise to press the two bearing ends together once I have the tabs lined up on each of the eight corners. This presses them together evenly.

This project contains an electrical function. Electrical shock resulting in injury or death can occur. If you are not experienced with working with electricity do not attempt this project. description.text:
all credits to Chris for this great project: https://www.thingiverse.com/TheChrisP
i just made a small modification so that the display reads all 3 particle sizes and thus removed the temp sensor hole from the model.

For the Original instructions please read ChrisP's thing:https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2320020

I do have some NOOB tips to share my experience as a total arduino noob. Perhaps it helps other builders.
Perhaps all is obvious for experienced people...i was not :-)

Download and install Arduino IDE (https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software)
First of all the programming; you need to add the ESP8266 arduino extension to IDE:

Start Arduino and open Preferences window.
Enter arduino.esp8266.com/stable/package_esp8266com_index.json into Additional Board Manager URLs field. You can add multiple URLs, separating them with commas.
Open Boards Manager from Tools > Board menu and install esp8266 platform
select your ESP8266 board from Tools > Board menu after installation.
Load the sketch file into IDE.
If you now press the compile button you get a bunch of errors because IDE is missing some librarys.
You need to add all missing libs via Sketch->Inc. Library->Manage Library: there search for the reported missing lib until all lib's are installed and there is no longer a missing library.
Now your you should be able to send the code to the ESP2866

Regarding the components, i made the mistake that i reversed the PMS5003 color code (red and black was NOT the power)
Pin 1 is actually on the right. In my case the coloring of the schematic on github was correct, For me just reversed.

Eventually i changed the sketch so that there are no temp and Humid reading, But mine display's all 3 particle values.

description.text: This is a guide for section rodent brains into 1 mm sections at room temperature. It has a base and a frame. I first place the frame on a piece of gauze. Then place the brain on the gauze and in the frame. The ventral surface of the brain is facing up for identifying the land marks. I then place two razor blades into the slots to get a 1 mm section. The entire assembly (gauze, frame, brain, blades) are then moved onto the base. Pushing the assembly down into the base release the two blades, together with the slice of the brain.This can then be dropped into cold aCSF or saline.
The design is in FreeCAD format.

title: Prusa i3 MK2 MultiMaterial - Switch PCB Case for Rev 0.4 (new and smaller PCB)

description.text:
When I installed my MultiMaterial upgrade for the Original Prusa i3 MK2S printer, I accidentally broke the casing for the extruder switch PCB.

The original case can be found here:
https://github.com/prusa3d/Original-Prusa-i3/tree/Multi-Material-Upgrade/Printed-Parts/stl

However, the original is not deep enough (in my opinion) so that squeezing all cables in is a pain and caused my original case to break in the first place. Okay, this was my fault because I used too much force. Nevertheless, a design should not provoke you to do so, right?

My case is still compatible with the original cover plate. However, I have also recreated this cover as well, mainly because of two reasons.

  1. To provide a complete set! :-)
  2. Because my case is over 10 mm deeper and has wider and longer slots/holes for the cables.

I made the case deeper because of the reasons mentioned above, which makes the storage of the very long stepper cables easier.

The wider and longer slots make cable routing easier. However, with the original cover plate, you will have large unused areas of the slots/holes after mounting. My cover plate also provides covers for these unused spaces.

I hope my design is useful for some of you.

You will also find the Fusion 360 file to make your changes - but please respect the licensing that applies to this project and its files.

Your opinion on this design and suggestions to make it even better is appreciated

Please also take a look at my other designs, printer parts and tools.

If you like to support me and my work, please consider to follow me

  • here at Thingiverse
  • Twitter
  • Instagram
  • YouTube
Sending a tip over Thingiverse will buy me some coffee to stay productive. :-)

Thank you very much.

title: DIY Car radio replacement
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Where I live there is always a chance that your car radio will get stolen and it happened to me already for a view times.
Unfortunately its not cheap to restore the damage on your car after that.
For this car radio manufacturers have made a removable front on there car radio's with the idea that the radio has no value without them.
This would then prevent that the radio will be stolen.
But unfortunately after a while the contacts between the radio and removable front get bad.
Then, every time you want to use your radio,you find yourself struggling to get it working the way it suppose to.
This is a problem I found with all car radios I had in the past.
Then the features that takes over you radio trough the radio ether.
At one moment you are listening to a song from a USB stick, the other moment you music is being stopped because a “important announcement” is being made on the radio.
I do not like that very much.
Also I do not even listen to radio. I only listen to mp3 from USB.
So I decided to replace my car radio for something that is not desirable for theft and that would keep working over time.
Something that would keep working on speed bumps :-).
I have a smartphone as a MP3 player. And I have an old amplifier.
With a cheap 6 euro blue-tooth module the phone can even auto connect to my amplifier.
The only thing I needed was something to hold these things together and swap this with my car radio.
The idea is that it looks like a panel that covers a hole in the dashboard.
There are buttons on it to switch the amplifier, blue-tooth and a LM317 for 5v power.
Also there is a button to switch analogue or blue-tooth input to the amplifier.
The LM317 feeds the phone and the blue-tooth module. Also included a clip to hold my phone.
If somebody would to steal it still, for these parts I lost nothing in money,
because I had these parts laying around doing nothing anyways :-).
The little hole between the first 2 red button makes it possible for me to adjust the volume pot of the amplifier, if necessary.
The USB port is only for charging the phone.

title: LattePanda Turbine - fan cooler mount for the panda

description.text:
Since the LattePanda suffers from overheating, I created this design to mount a standard 80mm computer case fan to the side of it. 80mm fan coolers are very efficient and silent and therefore better suitable for a quiet cooling solution. Smaller sizes tend to compensate the smaller blade size with higher speed and are therefore louder. I will be using this with a "be quiet!" Pure Wings 2, which is available for about 10€.

Update 1: the first print just arrived and fitted surprisingly well! I didn't have to do any additional drilling or grinding.
The cooler gets a bit louder than without the tube due to the tailback of air from the funnel, but that's still quite silent compared to the smaller high RPM coolers.

The temperature decreased from about 60° when idle with passive cooling (which you can see in the pictures) to about 42°. Unfortunately I don't have any numbers from a 20mm cooler, but given the noise it creates, it wasn't an option for me.

Update 2: After the first print I updated the design to optimize the airflow underneath the board (where the processor is located). I also simplified and cleaned up the mesh.

This is a motor focuser for a GSO Monorail focuser with 1:10 fine focus.
It uses the code from https://github.com/fehlfarbe/arduino-motorfocus

bom:

  • 4x M3x20mm DIN912 for mounting to the focuser
  • 2x M3x10mm DIN912 and 2x M3 locknuts for mounting the stepper motor
  • 1x stepper motor + board (5V 28BYJ-48 with ULN2003 driver board)
  • 5V Arduino nano clone (ATmega328P CH340 chip)
  • 6x female-female 200mm jumper cables

The Arduino Pins D3-6 connect to the IN4-1 on the driver board. GND and Vin as well.
(D3-IN4, D4-IN3, D5-IN2, D6-IN1)

I programmed the Arduino on Linux with the Arduino IDE (Arduino Nano Board with ATmega328p CPU). You need to be in the correct usergroup to access the ttyUSBx port.

I uses Indilib to drive the Arduino focuser as it uses the moonlite protocol.

Hint: You need to get the motor in before securing the PCB. (maybe a future version will be easier to assemble)
